<section class="module content">
  <div class="container">
    <p>The current status quo has left many rural women with little social mobility, an economy that is moving the good paying jobs to cities, and for some, severe poverty.</p>
    <p>Many intersectional feminists have focused on issues surrounding economic justice for years now -- but mainly in urban areas. There has been little outreach to women in rural areas. Ultimately, the electoral success of feminist issues depends on gaining the support of rural women. Similarly, rural women must join forces with the intersectional feminist movement to overcome their current economic challenges.</p>
    <p>We are a group of rural women who are choosing to find common ground between ourselves and the feminist movement. We will organize and fight for our core values. We will not resort to the divisive, offensive, sexist, racist, homophobic, or classist rhetoric that is prevalent in today’s political climate.</p>
    <p>Neither of the two major political parties have specifically addressed the issues that affect rural women. Rather than engaging with our issues, they choose to continue pushing policies that benefit their corporate donors. As such, we are purposefully not affiliated with either of them, but we will support politicians with a demonstrable record of fighting for our core values.</p>
    <p>For further reading, please see the following websites and articles.</p>
  </div>
</section>

